  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "8zdljEKy4VONpYuPhCYzrrimTtk=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:32.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Dispersed replicas via `RedundancyLevel` \u2014 additive, reversible\n\nbee-js exposes:\n\n```ts\nenum RedundancyLevel { OFF=0, MEDIUM=1, STRONG=2, INSANE=3, PARANOID=4 }\nenum RedundancyStrategy { NONE, DATA, PROX, RACE }\n```\n\nUploading with `{ redundancyLevel: MEDIUM }` makes Bee erasure-code the chunks across the neighbourhood. The default download strategy cascade is `NONE \u2192 DATA \u2192 PROX \u2192 RACE`, so existing readers transparently benefit \u2014 no reader-side code changes needed.\n\nThis is **not** the paper's literal balanced-SOC-replica pattern (paper \u00a75.1.3) but achieves the same outcome through Reed-Solomon coding, as a one-field opt-in with zero protocol changes.\n\n**Why it's low-risk:**\n- No schema changes, no wire-protocol changes, no feed-shape changes.\n- ACT layering is unaffected \u2014 redundancy operates on chunks, ACT on their contents.\n- Rolling back = revert the 2\u20133 line flag additions.\n- Zero behavioural change if `RedundancyLevel.OFF` (default).",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:32.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:32.000Z"
    }
  },
